        <!-- Chapter 2 -->
        <h2 id="create-extension">2. Create an extension</h2>

        <p>
          Extensions are SIP accounts assigned to phones or softphones.
          Each extension has its own number, SIP password, and caller ID.
        </p>

        <h3>Create a new extension</h3>
        <ol>
          <li>Go to <strong>Settings → Extensions</strong></li>
          <li>Click <strong>“New extension”</strong></li>
          <li>Fill in the fields:
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Number</strong> – e.g., 1001, 1002 (must be unique)</li>
              <li><strong>Name</strong> – e.g., “Office” or “Max Mustermann”</li>
              <li><strong>Password</strong> – SIP password (auto-generated, can be changed)</li>
              <li><strong>Caller ID</strong> – Display name for internal calls</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li>Click <strong>“Save”</strong></li>
        </ol>

        <h3>Configure a softphone or handset</h3>
        <p>Set up your device with these values:</p>
        <table style="width:100%;border-collapse:collapse;margin:24px 0;">
          <thead>
            <tr style="border-bottom:2px solid #e2e8f0;text-align:left;">
              <th style="padding:12px 16px;color:#4a5568;">Field</th>
              <th style="padding:12px 16px;color:#4a5568;">Value</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr style="border-bottom:1px solid #e2e8f0;">
              <td style="padding:12px 16px;">SIP server</td>
              <td style="padding:12px 16px;">IP address of your GonoPBX server</td>
            </tr>
            <tr style="border-bottom:1px solid #e2e8f0;">
              <td style="padding:12px 16px;">Username</td>
              <td style="padding:12px 16px;">Extension number (e.g., 1001)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr style="border-bottom:1px solid #e2e8f0;">
              <td style="padding:12px 16px;">Password</td>
              <td style="padding:12px 16px;">SIP password of the extension</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td style="padding:12px 16px;">Transport</td>
              <td style="padding:12px 16px;">UDP (default port 5060)</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>

        <div class="blog-info-box">
          <p>
            <strong>Tip:</strong> Registration status is shown live in the dashboard and under Settings → Extensions
            (green dot = registered).
          </p>
        </div>

        <!-- Chapter 3 -->
        <h2 id="sip-trunk">3. Configure a SIP trunk</h2>

        <p>
          A SIP trunk connects your PBX to a SIP provider,
          allowing calls via the public telephone network.
        </p>

        <h3>Create a new trunk</h3>
        <ol>
          <li>Go to <strong>Settings → Lines</strong></li>
          <li>Click <strong>“New trunk”</strong></li>
          <li>Enter the provider data:
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Name</strong> – e.g., “Plusnet” or “sipgate”</li>
              <li><strong>SIP server</strong> – Registrar address of the provider</li>
              <li><strong>Username</strong> – SIP username from the provider</li>
              <li><strong>Password</strong> – SIP password from the provider</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li>Click <strong>“Save”</strong></li>
        </ol>

        <h3>Check registration status</h3>
        <p>
          After saving, GonoPBX registers with the provider automatically.
          You can see the status:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>On the <strong>Dashboard</strong> under “Active lines”</li>
          <li>Under <strong>Settings → Lines</strong> (green = registered, red = error)</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="blog-info-box">
          <p>
            <strong>Tip:</strong> If registration fails, verify the credentials
            and make sure SIP port 5060/UDP is open in your firewall.
            Use <a href="#sip-debug">SIP Debug</a> for troubleshooting.
          </p>
        </div>

        <!-- Chapter 4 -->
        <h2 id="dids">4. Assign DIDs</h2>

        <p>
          Inbound numbers (DIDs) must be assigned to extensions
          so calls are routed to the correct phones.
        </p>

        <h3>Import DIDs</h3>
        <ol>
          <li>Go to <strong>DIDs</strong> in the main menu</li>
          <li>Click <strong>“Add DID”</strong></li>
          <li>Enter the number in <code>+49xxx</code> format</li>
          <li>Select the assigned <strong>trunk</strong></li>
        </ol>

        <h3>Assign a DID to an extension</h3>
        <ol>
          <li>Select the desired DID in the list</li>
          <li>Assign it to an <strong>extension</strong> via the dropdown</li>
          <li>The change takes effect immediately</li>
        </ol>

        <h3>Configure outbound caller ID</h3>
        <p>
          Under <strong>Settings → Extensions</strong> you can define per extension
          which DID is shown for outbound calls. Optionally, the
          <code>P-Asserted-Identity</code> header can be used for providers that require it.
        </p>

        <!-- Chapter 5 -->
        <h2 id="call-forwarding">5. Configure call forwarding</h2>

        <p>
          Call forwarding sends inbound calls to other destinations —
          for example to a mobile phone, another extension, or voicemail.
        </p>

        <h3>Forwarding types</h3>
        <table style="width:100%;border-collapse:collapse;margin:24px 0;">
          <thead>
            <tr style="border-bottom:2px solid #e2e8f0;text-align:left;">
              <th style="padding:12px 16px;color:#4a5568;">Type</th>
              <th style="padding:12px 16px;color:#4a5568;">Description</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr style="border-bottom:1px solid #e2e8f0;">
              <td style="padding:12px 16px;"><strong>Immediate</strong></td>
              <td style="padding:12px 16px;">All calls are forwarded immediately without ringing</td>
            </tr>
            <tr style="border-bottom:1px solid #e2e8f0;">
              <td style="padding:12px 16px;"><strong>Busy</strong></td>
              <td style="padding:12px 16px;">Forward only when the extension is busy</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td style="padding:12px 16px;"><strong>No Answer</strong></td>
              <td style="padding:12px 16px;">Forward after a set number of rings (timeout)</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>

        <h3>Set up call forwarding</h3>
        <ol>
          <li>Go to <strong>Call Forwarding</strong> in the main menu</li>
          <li>Select the <strong>extension</strong> you want to configure</li>
          <li>Select the <strong>type</strong> (Immediate, Busy, or No Answer)</li>
          <li>Enter the <strong>destination</strong> – an internal extension (e.g., <code>1002</code>) or an external number (e.g., <code>0171xxxxxxx</code>)</li>
          <li>Enable forwarding via the <strong>toggle</strong></li>
        </ol>

        <div class="blog-info-box">
          <p>
            <strong>Tip:</strong> You can configure multiple forwarding types at once.
            Example: No Answer → voicemail and Busy → mobile phone.
          </p>
        </div>

        <!-- Chapter 6 -->
        <h2 id="voicemail">6. Set up voicemail</h2>

        <p>
          Voicemail lets callers leave a message when an extension is not reachable.
          Messages can be delivered via email.
        </p>

        <h3>Configure SMTP server</h3>
        <p>To enable voicemail notifications, configure an SMTP server first:</p>
        <ol>
          <li>Go to <strong>Settings → Email</strong></li>
          <li>Enter the SMTP data:
            <ul>
              <li><strong>SMTP server</strong> – e.g., <code>smtp.gmail.com</code></li>
              <li><strong>Port</strong> – e.g., <code>587</code> (TLS) or <code>465</code> (SSL)</li>
              <li><strong>Username</strong> and <strong>Password</strong></li>
              <li><strong>Sender address</strong></li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li>Click <strong>“Send test email”</strong> to verify the configuration</li>
        </ol>

        <h3>Enable voicemail per extension</h3>
        <ol>
          <li>Go to <strong>Settings → Extensions</strong></li>
          <li>Edit the desired extension</li>
          <li>Enable <strong>Voicemail</strong></li>
          <li>Set a <strong>PIN</strong> (for phone access to the mailbox)</li>
          <li>Enter the <strong>email address</strong> for notifications</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="blog-info-box">
          <p>
            <strong>Note:</strong> Voicemails can also be listened to and managed
            directly in the web GUI under <strong>Voicemail</strong> in the main menu.
          </p>
        </div>

        <!-- Chapter 7 -->
        <h2 id="users">7. Create users</h2>

        <p>
          GonoPBX supports multiple users with different roles.
          Admins have full access, regular users see only their own extension.
        </p>

        <h3>Create a new user</h3>
        <ol>
          <li>Go to <strong>Settings → Users</strong></li>
          <li>Click <strong>“New user”</strong></li>
          <li>Fill in the fields:
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Username</strong> – Login name</li>
              <li><strong>Password</strong> – Automatically generated</li>
              <li><strong>Role</strong> – <code>admin</code> or <code>user</code></li>
              <li><strong>Extension</strong> – Assign to an existing extension</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li>Click <strong>“Save”</strong></li>
        </ol>

        <h3>Roles at a glance</h3>
        <table style="width:100%;border-collapse:collapse;margin:24px 0;">
          <thead>
            <tr style="border-bottom:2px solid #e2e8f0;text-align:left;">
              <th style="padding:12px 16px;color:#4a5568;">Area</th>
              <th style="padding:12px 16px;color:#4a5568;">Admin</th>
              <th style="padding:12px 16px;color:#4a5568;">User</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr style="border-bottom:1px solid #e2e8f0;">
              <td style="padding:12px 16px;">Dashboard</td>
              <td style="padding:12px 16px;">Full</td>
              <td style="padding:12px 16px;">Limited</td>
            </tr>
            <tr style="border-bottom:1px solid #e2e8f0;">
              <td style="padding:12px 16px;">Settings</td>
              <td style="padding:12px 16px;">All tabs</td>
              <td style="padding:12px 16px;">No access</td>
            </tr>
            <tr style="border-bottom:1px solid #e2e8f0;">
              <td style="padding:12px 16px;">Call history</td>
              <td style="padding:12px 16px;">All calls</td>
              <td style="padding:12px 16px;">Own only</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td style="padding:12px 16px;">Voicemail</td>
              <td style="padding:12px 16px;">All mailboxes</td>
              <td style="padding:12px 16px;">Own only</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>

        <!-- Chapter 8 -->
        <h2 id="security">8. Security</h2>

        <p>
          GonoPBX provides multiple security features to protect your PBX
          from unauthorized access and abuse.
        </p>

        <h3>IP whitelist for SIP</h3>
        <ol>
          <li>Go to <strong>Settings → Security</strong></li>
          <li>Under <strong>“IP whitelist”</strong> add IP addresses or CIDR ranges</li>
          <li>Only allowed IPs can register as SIP endpoints</li>
        </ol>

        <h3>Fail2Ban</h3>
        <p>
          Fail2Ban protects against brute force attacks by banning IPs after
          too many failed login attempts.
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Jails</strong> – Overview of active Fail2Ban jails (e.g., <code>asterisk</code>)</li>
          <li><strong>Active bans</strong> – View currently banned IP addresses</li>
          <li><strong>Unban</strong> – Unblock a banned IP with one click</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Password strength checks</h3>
        <p>
          Under <strong>Settings → Security</strong> GonoPBX shows an overview
          of extensions with weak SIP passwords. Weak passwords are marked
          in red and should be changed immediately.
        </p>

        <div class="blog-info-box">
          <p>
            <strong>Important:</strong> Always use strong, randomly generated SIP passwords.
            Weak passwords are the most common entry point for SIP abuse (toll fraud).
          </p>
        </div>

        <!-- Chapter 9 -->
        <h2 id="sip-debug">9. Use SIP Debug</h2>

        <p>
          The built-in SIP Debug shows all SIP messages in real time —
          directly in the browser, without SSH.
        </p>

        <h3>Start capture</h3>
        <ol>
          <li>Go to <strong>SIP Debug</strong> in the main menu</li>
          <li>Click <strong>“Start capture”</strong></li>
          <li>Make the problematic call</li>
          <li>Stop the capture</li>
        </ol>

        <h3>Read SIP messages</h3>
        <p>
          Recorded SIP messages are grouped by <strong>Call-ID</strong>.
          Click an entry to view the full SIP text:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>INVITE</strong> – Call setup (contains From, To, SDP)</li>
          <li><strong>100 Trying / 180 Ringing / 200 OK</strong> – Responses from the destination</li>
          <li><strong>BYE</strong> – Call termination</li>
          <li><strong>REGISTER</strong> – Registration attempts</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Diagnose common issues</h3>
        <table style="width:100%;border-collapse:collapse;margin:24px 0;">
          <thead>
            <tr style="border-bottom:2px solid #e2e8f0;text-align:left;">
              <th style="padding:12px 16px;color:#4a5568;">Symptom</th>
              <th style="padding:12px 16px;color:#4a5568;">What to look for</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr style="border-bottom:1px solid #e2e8f0;">
              <td style="padding:12px 16px;">No ringing</td>
              <td style="padding:12px 16px;">Does an INVITE arrive? Does the destination respond with 180?</td>
            </tr>
            <tr style="border-bottom:1px solid #e2e8f0;">
              <td style="padding:12px 16px;">One-way audio</td>
              <td style="padding:12px 16px;">Check SDP – do IPs and ports match?</td>
            </tr>
            <tr style="border-bottom:1px solid #e2e8f0;">
              <td style="padding:12px 16px;">Registration fails</td>
              <td style="padding:12px 16px;">REGISTER → 401 → REGISTER with auth → expect 200 OK</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td style="padding:12px 16px;">Call drops</td>
              <td style="padding:12px 16px;">Search for BYE – who ends the call and why?</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>

        <!-- Chapter 10 -->
        <h2 id="update">10. Run a system update</h2>

        <p>
          GonoPBX can be updated either via the web GUI or manually via the command line.
        </p>

        <h3>Via the web GUI</h3>
        <ol>
          <li>Go to <strong>Settings → Server</strong></li>
          <li>Under <strong>“Update”</strong> you can see if a new version is available</li>
          <li>Click <strong>“Install update”</strong></li>
          <li>GonoPBX restarts automatically</li>
        </ol>

        <h3>Manually via command line</h3>
        <div style="background:#1a202c;color:#e2e8f0;padding:20px 24px;border-radius:8px;margin:24px 0;font-family:monospace;font-size:0.95rem;overflow-x:auto;">
          <span style="color:#68d391;">$</span> cd /root/gonopbx<br/>
          <span style="color:#68d391;">$</span> git pull<br/>
          <span style="color:#68d391;">$</span> docker compose up -d --build
        </div>

        <div class="blog-info-box">
          <p>
            <strong>Note:</strong> Updates restart the containers. Active calls will be interrupted.
            Run updates outside business hours when possible.
          </p>
        </div>

      </div>
